Some machine learning¶

Let's split the data into two parts -- train data (we will use cross-validation on it) and a hold-out set.

We don't have much data, especially we don't have many 1's, so it's better to use cv, instead of train-val-test split. But we still have some hold-out to check our unbiased performance. Moreover, we need to stratify the data according to the initial distribution.

In [15]:
feature_columns = [col for col in merged_df.columns if col != "Sickness"]

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(merged_df[feature_columns],
                                                    merged_df["Sickness"], 
                                                    stratify=merged_df["Sickness"], 
                                                    test_size=0.25, random_state=RANDOM_STATE)
In [16]:
# We will also keep track of our models to compare their predictions (if the person is sick) in the end

error_analysis = pd.DataFrame(columns=['pca_log_reg', 'select_from_model_log_reg'], index=X_test.index)

Let us start with something simple and powerful -- logistic regression. We can create a simple pipeline to find best parameters using GridSearch.

We will look (and ask our algorithms to look) for better recall of the class 1, because we can make some false positives, but we want to keep false negative as low as possible. In other words, we want to detect all (as many as possible) sick people and it's OK for us to confuse some healthy guy with a sick one.

In [17]:
# Scale for better convergence

scaler = StandardScaler()  

C_values = [0.001, 0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 1.]

param_grid = {'logisticregression__C': C_values, 
              'logisticregression__penalty': ['l1', 'l2']}

clf = LogisticRegression(random_state=RANDOM_STATE)

pipeline = make_pipeline(scaler, clf)

estimator = GridSearchCV(pipeline, param_grid=param_grid, scoring='recall', cv=3)
estimator.fit(X_train, y_train)

print("Mean recall for the 1 class across the folds on cv: {0} \n".format(estimator.best_score_))
print("Best estimator: \n {0} \n".format(estimator.best_estimator_))
print("Classification report for holdout: \n", classification_report(y_test, 
                                                                    estimator.best_estimator_.predict(X_test)))

error_analysis['log_reg'] =  estimator.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

The mean recall on cv is 0.71, which is not that high as it is in the hold-out (simply more samples). The precision for 1 class is quite low, seems the algorithm is too aggresively tries to put everyone in sick class. Another way to justify it -- just look at the C value, it's pretty low (0.001), so gridSearch tried to find optimal parameters from given set to increase recall of the 1 class.

We can try to do better. We have many features, maybe we can try to reduce the dimensionality (using PCA for example) for obtaining (hopefully) more informative features. Later we can try to select the features based on the model (using feature importance weights)

Let us try to do feature selection with the help of the model, I will use simple logreg as a baseline.

In [19]:
scaler = StandardScaler()  

param_grid = {'logisticregression__C': [0.001, 0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 1., 1.2],
              'logisticregression__penalty': ['l1', 'l2'],
              'selectfrommodel__estimator__C': [0.05, 0.1, 1., 1.2], 
              'selectfrommodel__estimator__penalty': ['l1', 'l2'],
              'selectfrommodel__threshold': ['mean', 'median', None]
             }

lr = LogisticRegression(random_state=RANDOM_STATE)

fs = SelectFromModel(estimator=lr)

pipeline = make_pipeline(scaler, fs, lr)

estimator = GridSearchCV(pipeline, param_grid=param_grid, scoring='recall', cv=3, n_jobs=-1)
estimator.fit(X_train, y_train)

print("Best mean recall for the 1 class across the folds on cv: {0} \n".format(estimator.best_score_))
print("Best estimator: \n {0} \n".format(estimator.best_estimator_))
print("Classification report for holdout: \n", classification_report(y_test, 
                                                                    estimator.best_estimator_.predict(X_test)))

error_analysis['select_from_model_log_reg'] =  estimator.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

Let's look at the coefficients of the model, they will tell us more about important features. Later we can compare these features on the objects, where the model made a mistake.

In [23]:
clf = estimator.best_estimator_.named_steps['logisticregression']

# we will take abs() here, though it would be better 
# to study both pos and neg coefs as they "push" to different classes

feature_importance = abs(clf.coef_[0])
feature_importance = 100.0 * (feature_importance / feature_importance.max())
# let's take top 10
sorted_idx = np.argsort(feature_importance)[:10]
pos = np.arange(sorted_idx.shape[0]) + .5

featfig = plt.figure()
featax = featfig.add_subplot(1, 1, 1)
featax.barh(pos, feature_importance[sorted_idx], align='center')
featax.set_yticks(pos)
featax.set_yticklabels(np.array(X_train.columns)[sorted_idx], fontsize=8)
featax.set_xlabel('Relative Feature Importance')

plt.tight_layout()   
plt.show()

Here are the things, for which I didn't have time:

  1. make 'make_pipeline' flexible and get rid of the repeatable code (though I always do it for production and after some time with research notebooks)
  2. better feature importance exploration. The way the model makes its predictions is crucial, so I would explore key features and maybe find some leakages or insights. This exploration will also lead to discovery of potential outliers -- sick (healthy) people with normal (abnormal) features.
  3. we can use several algorithms to blend or stack their predictions. As we saw logreg is pretty brutal.
  4. I didn't check for crazy values, though I should look at them. Also I haven't paid any attention to the std of the folds on cv, but this is also important if we want to find some outliers.
  5. I will definitely try something special for imbalanced class problems (synthetic examples generation or clever sampling). I've been researching this area, you can check this out if you want to: https://github.com/egorLab/tutorials-and-posts/blob/master/imbalanced_problems_labintcev_english.ipynb
  6. I didn't try any feature engineering, though even simple multiplications and squaring could work.

Here are the things, which didn't work:

  1. k-best feature_selection with SelectKBest, f_classif, mutual_info_classif.
  2. tree models and ensembles on top of pca.
  3. VarianceThreshold feature selection.
